PREFACE.

I'r has been thought desirable to adopt for the present edition of the Aeneid a standard text, and to adhere to it throughout, without any variation, even in those few pas- sages where the editor might prefer a change of reading. Accordingly the revised text of Jahn, as one of the most faultless and reliable, and as the ono at present, perhaps, most, generally approved, has been carcfully reprinted from the German edition, as the basis of the school com- mentary here offered to the American student.

The notes have been derived from most of the ablest commentatore on the Aeneid, and more especially from Heyne, Wagner, Thiel, and Forbiger. The editor has also frequently consulted the numerous school and col lege editions, and is particularly indebted to the admira- ble commentaries of Theodore Ladewig and A. H. Bryce, recently published, the former in Berlin, and the latter in London and Glasgow.
